===Etymology===
{{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|saphir|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|sapphirus|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|σάπφειρος|ἡ σάπφειρος|lang=grc|[[precious]] [[stone]], [[gem]]}} (2nd decl.; transliterated /sápfiros/ in [http://concordances.org/greek/4552.htm Biblos - Strong's Greek, entry 4552], sometimes spelt ''σάμφειρος'' in [http://www.openelibrary.info/index.php/list/4-griechisch-deutsches-handworterbuch/3,Σ,Ά,.xhtml Griechisch-deutsches Handwörterbuch] or unusually hyphened as ''σάπ-φειρος'' by Leander van Ess in "Hē palaia diathēkē kata tous hebdomēkonta" published in 1835), from a Semitic language (compare Hebrew {{term|סַפִּיר|lang=he|tr=sappir}} (compare [http://concordances.org/hebrew/5601.htm Strong's Concordance: entry 5601], probably ultimately from a non-Semitic source such as Sanskrit {{term|शनिप्रिय|tr=śanipriya|lang=sa||dear to Saturn}} and [[dark-coloured]] [[stone]] (compare [http://spokensanskrit.de/index.php?script=DI&beginning=0+&tinput=%E0%A4%B6%E0%A4%A8%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%AA%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%AF&trans=Translate&direction=SE Sanskrit Dictionary for Spoken Sanskrit]).

